issue.title: Allow to configure schema in postgres driver
issue.body:
Thanks for this great piece of software!

I'd like to propose an improvement:

I'm using the same Postgres database (in Supabase) for sidequest and the rest of my application. While sidequest takes care of its tables automatically, my application's tables are managed with Drizzle ORM. This leads to a collision whenever I deploy a new schema, because I don't have schemas defined for the sidequest tables, therefore Drizzle wants to delete them.

It would be great if I could tell sidequest to use its own schema for its tables.

I know that some Postgres drives support selecting the schema by appending `?currentSchema=sidequest` to the connection url. This would be a simple solution, but this does not work with Supabase.

Therefore it would be great if I could configure the schema in the sidequest config:

```typescript
  Sidequest.configure({
    backend: {
      driver: '@sidequest/postgres-backend',
      config: process.env.DATABASE_URL,
      schema: 'sidequest' // proposed new entry. Optional, defaults to 'public'
    }
  })
```

I couldn't find any config entry like this, so I propose to add it.

Let me know what you think about this or if there already is a solution that I'm not aware of.

Cheers
Fred

comment.body:
Thx for the quick response.

I think the issue for me was that `BackendConfig.config` is of type `unknown`, so I get no hint that this could be an object (and of course I will get no hint about the shape of that object either) and all examples in the docs are with a connection string only.

The tip is in the docs (thanks for pointing it out) but easily read over.

It would be great to have proper type hints for the config and also an actual example in the docs.

pull_request.title: Set pango language through ctx.lang
pull_request.body: This would set pango's language through the Canvas context ( `ctx.lang`, docs: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/CanvasRenderingContext2D/lang ) My goal was to fix issues where the same Unicode codepoint should appear differently in Simplified Chinese, Traditional Chinese, and Japanese (as an example: lang=zh é—¨ vs. lang=ja é—¨). This can be done with language-specific fonts, but modern fonts often support all options and use the lang tag. Han unification: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Han_unification Related issue for Chrome client-side canvas: https://github.com/mapbox/tiny-sdf/pull/58 I'm submitting the code and test as a draft PR because **this is still failing** to change the output. I did rebuild bindings, and tried with and without `pango_cairo_update_layout`. Other ideas: this is failing to set the language, setting it at the wrong time, the fonts or something needs to be reset, or pango handles Han unification using something else? I'm a longtime node-canvas user but new to the internals. I found this reference to `PANGO_LANGUAGE` and `%PANGO_SCRIPT_HAN` https://github.com/gtk-rs/gir-files/blob/main/Pango-1.0.gir#L11631

/var/log/onlyoffice/documentserver/nginx.error.log reports:
`
2025/08/17 15:50:59 [error] 17189#420269: *17 kevent() reported that connect() failed (61: Connection refused) while connecting to upstream, client: fd30:455f:866e::80, server: , request: "GET /heathcheck HTTP/1.1", upstream: "http://[::1]:8000/heathcheck", host: "$domain"
`
However, no service is actually listening on port 8000:
`
# jexec office sockstat -l                                                                    1m11s 
USER     COMMAND    PID   FD  PROTO  LOCAL ADDRESS         FOREIGN ADDRESS      
www      nginx      30822 10  tcp4   10.0.0.51:80          *:*
www      nginx      30822 16  tcp6   *:80                  *:*
root     nginx      63024 10  tcp4   10.0.0.51:80          *:*
root     nginx      63024 16  tcp6   *:80                  *:*
onlyoffice metrics  25846 16  tcp46  *:8126                *:*
onlyoffice metrics  25846 17  udp4   10.0.0.51:8125        *:*
root     python3.11 22938 5   stream /var/run/supervisor/supervisor.sock.22538
rabbitmq epmd       18896 3   tcp4   10.0.0.51:4369        *:*
rabbitmq epmd       18896 4   tcp6   *:4369                *:*
rabbitmq beam.smp   10052 16  tcp4   10.0.0.51:25672       *:*
rabbitmq beam.smp   10052 33  tcp6   *:5672                *:*
rabbitmq beam.smp   10052 34  tcp4   10.0.0.51:5672        *:*
root     syslogd    23474 5   dgram  /var/run/log <- 
root     syslogd    23474 6   dgram  /var/run/logpriv
`

### Reproduction Steps

1. Create ONLYOFFICE jail (named `office` in my case)
2. Install ONLYOFFICE-docservier in the jail: `# pkg -j office install -y onlyoffice-documentserver`
3. Follow the instructions returned by pkg:
  1. Enable services at startup in the /etc/rc.conf file â€“ obvious
  2. Install a database server and set up the database â€“ I used an existing mariadb server and hooked it up
  3. Create a new rabbitmq user for the ONLYOFFICE Document Server configuration â€“ no issues here
  4. Set up supervisord in order to execute documentserver services â€“ again, seems fine
  5. Set up nginx â€“ it is unclear, where exactly to put the include statement. Inside the http block, but outside any server blocks seems right.
  6. run documentserver-update-securelink.sh â€“ the script fails due to invalid characters. Setting the variable to a randomly generated string instead of the generator directive circumvented the issue.
4. Set up basic proxying (with SSL) on preexisting web server
5. Access https://$domain/heathcheck
6. Observe the error messages mentioned above, indicating that the request is proxied to the appropriate nginx instance, but no service is actually listening to port 8000 there.

### Additional information

The Operating System is **NOT** Docker, but this form won't let me create an issue without selecting at least one item, but none apply to me (docker doesn't even run on FreeBSD). I installed `onlyoffice-documentserver` via `pkg` in a FreeBSD jail.

supervisord, rabbitmq and nginx are running in the jail:
`
# service -j office -e | grep /usr/local
/usr/local/etc/rc.d/supervisord
/usr/local/etc/rc.d/rabbitmq
/usr/local/etc/rc.d/nginx
`

supervisord reports that the ONLYOFFICE services are indeed running:
`
# jexec office supervisorctl status all 
ds:converter                     RUNNING   pid 33418, uptime 1:19:43
ds:docservice                    RUNNING   pid 68939, uptime 1:02:11
ds:metrics                       RUNNING   pid 25846, uptime 2:09:22
`

/var/log/onlyoffice/documentserver/docservice/err.log is empty.

/var/log/onlyoffice/documentserver/docservice/out.log and /var/log/rabbitmq/rabbit@office.log show no current errors or warnings.

/var/log/supervisord.log only complains about missing authentication (which is irrelevant due to being inside a jail, and also shouldn't have anything to do with the issue at hand).

Both host and jail are on FreeBSD 14.3-RELEASE GENERIC arm64

pull_request.title: anki: 25.02.5 -> 25.07.2
pull_request.body:
This includes needing to migrate to a 'uv' based packaging system, since
that's what upstream did.

Unfortunately, `uv sync` as a FoD doesn't work since it's not a stable
output format.

I handled it by writing a hacky "uv.lock to nix" converter (in the form
of the 'update.sh' script), and then using fetchurl to download every
file referenced in the uv.lock.

Using that, combined with the "UV_FIND_LINKS" environment variable lets
uv operate offline, so it seems like that's a good enough solution
there, phew!

The next hurdle was that anki wants us to populate 'pyenv' for an
offline build, and I wasn't sure the exact right 'uv' commands for that.
I ended up with a mix of 'uv export' to make requirements.txt files, and
'uv pip install' to install em. That seems to work okay for most things.

The final problem was that using anki's suggested version of PyQt hits
linker errors. To me, the easiest solution seemed like just using the
already-packaged pyqt packages from nixpkgs, so I did that.

Overall, this feels pragmatic and like it works.

I think the most compelling alternative would be to generate
"requirements.txt" using uv export, relax all the version requirements,
and use nixpkgs-packaged dependencies only.
I ended up not taking that route because not all of anki's dependencies
are present in nixpkgs, and so doing it like done in this PR seemed more
expedient.

That's the notes I have, hopefully this approach seems overall
reasonable!

Fixes #422471

feat: Implement comprehensive modeling framework with GUI

This commit delivers a complete, feature-rich hydraulic and hydrological modeling framework, built in response to user requests for a Preissmann-based model and a rapid modeling tool.

The project was developed in three main stages:

1.  **1D Hydraulic Model (`preissmann_model`)**:
    - A stable and verified model that solves the Saint-Venant equations using the implicit Preissmann scheme.
    - Includes support for hydraulic structures like `Gate` and `Pump` as internal boundary conditions.

2.  **Coupled Modeling Framework (`common` package)**:
    - A `BaseModelComponent` interface and `SimulationController` allow for connecting different model types (e.g., hydrological and hydraulic) into a single simulation.
    - Supports network topologies, including converging and diverging branches via a `Junction` component. This framework can handle any directed acyclic graph of model components.

3.  **Rapid Modeling GUI & Interface**:
    - A GUI built with the `eel` library for visually building model networks by dragging and dropping components, editing their properties, and defining connections.
    - A YAML configuration file format for defining models and networks without code.
    - A `ConfigParser` that reads the YAML file and automatically builds the simulation.
    - A generic `run_from_config.py` script to execute models directly from the configuration file.
    - The GUI provides real-time feedback during simulations, including a live log and a live plot of results. It also allows for post-simulation analysis and plotting.

The project is fully documented with a GUI manual and a comprehensive case study to demonstrate its capabilities.
